There is also a kind of gnat troublesome to some fruits, for instance acorns and figs, which appears to be bred from the sweet juice α secreted underneath the bark at that season; and indeed these trees are usually sickly.

Some influences of seasons or localities cannot properly be called diseases, since they cause instan- taneous death, for instance when a tree is attacked by wasting or blast, or by the effect of a special wind prevailing in a particular district, like the sirocco in Apulia or the Olympias wind in Euboea, which if it blows about midwinter shrivels up trees with dry cold so that no amount of subsequent sun- shine can revive them. This kind of blight infests narrow valleys and trees growing by rivers, and particularly vines, olive and fig rs; and when this 1135 occurred, it is at once detectedo at the budding season, though rather later 111 the case of olives.
